{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:45:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"181"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/181"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.79,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110423"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92687"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110423"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Pre-admission Clinic for assessment prior to an elective total knee replacement in one week. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation, mechanical aortic valve replacement, and hypertension. Her regular medications include digoxin, warfarin, and metoprolol. Her most recent International Normalised Ratio is 2.8 (2.5-3.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her heart sounds are regular with an audible mechanical click.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate perioperative anticoagulation strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue warfarin at current dose","Stop warfarin without bridging","Stop warfarin and bridge with enoxaparin","Reduce warfarin dose by 50%","Stop warfarin and bridge with clopidogrel"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has two high-risk indications for anticoagulation - a mechanical aortic valve and atrial fibrillation. Perioperative management of anticoagulation requires careful balance between preventing thromboembolism and avoiding surgical bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStop warfarin and bridge with enoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate strategy. Warfarin should be stopped 5 days before surgery to allow adequate washout. Therapeutic-dose enoxaparin is started when the International Normalised Ratio falls below 2.0, typically 2-3 days after stopping warfarin. The last dose should be given 12 hours before surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue warfarin at current dose\u003C/strong\u003E would create an unacceptable risk of major bleeding during surgery. Most surgical procedures require normalisation of coagulation parameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStop warfarin without bridging\u003C/strong\u003E would leave this high-risk patient unprotected from thromboembolism for too long. Mechanical heart valves have a very high risk of thrombosis when anticoagulation is subtherapeutic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce warfarin dose by 50%\u003C/strong\u003E would not achieve a safe International Normalised Ratio for surgery and would be difficult to titrate accurately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStop warfarin and bridge with clopidogrel\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as antiplatelet therapy does not provide adequate protection against valve thrombosis. Antiplatelet agents have a different mechanism of action from anticoagulants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with mechanical heart valves require bridging anticoagulation when warfarin is stopped pre-operatively due to high thromboembolic risk","Low molecular weight heparin is the preferred bridging agent, stopping 12 hours before surgery","Warfarin should be stopped 5 days before surgery to allow adequate washout"],"references":["Douketis JD, Spyropoulos AC, Kaatz S, Becker RC, Caprini JA, Dunn AS, Garcia DA, Jacobson A, Jaffer AK, Kong DF, Schulman S, Turpie AG, Hasselblad V, Ortel TL; BRIDGE Investigators. Perioperative Bridging Anticoagulation in Patients with Atrial Fibrillation. N Engl J Med. 2015 Aug 27;373(9):823-33. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa1501035. Epub 2015 Jun 22. PMID: 26095867; PMCID: PMC4931686.","Shaikh AY, McManus DD. A bridge too far? Findings of bridging anticoagulation use and outcomes in the Outcomes Registry for Better Informed Treatment of Atrial Fibrillation (ORBIT-AF). Circulation. 2015 Feb 3;131(5):448-50. doi: 10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.114.014319. Epub 2014 Dec 12. PMID: 25499874; PMCID: PMC4415256.","Siddiqui MU, Pasha AK, Rauf I, Lee JZ, Siddiqui MD, Yaacoub Y, Movahed MR. Efficacy and Safety of Perioperative Bridging Anticoagulation in Patients with Atrial Fibrillation Undergoing Elective Surgical Procedures: A Meta-analysis. Clin Med Res. 2021 Mar;19(1):19-25. doi: 10.3121/cmr.2020.1546. Epub 2020 Oct 14. PMID: 33060109; PMCID: PMC7987095."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92687"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"181"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92687"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T00:43:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T00:44:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110423"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relations